table_info.description: Confirmed Sample Company orders for a product, from a user.

db.description: Some example data for you to play around with.
db.name: Sample Database
db.caveats: You probably don't want to use this for your business-critical analyses, but hey, it's your world, we're just living in it.
db.points_of_interest: You can find all sorts of different joinable tables ranging from products to people to reviews here.

table_info.name: ORDERS
table_info.caveats: You can join this on the Products and Orders table using the ID fields. Discount is left null if not applicable.

fields.description: This is a unique ID for the product. It is also called the “Invoice number” or “Confirmation number” in customer facing emails and screens.
fields.name: ID

fields.description: The id of the user who made this order. Note that in some cases where an order was created on behalf of a customer who phoned the order in, this might be the employee who handled the request.
fields.name: USER_ID

target.description: A unique identifier given to each user.
target.name: ID

fields.description: The product ID. This is an internal identifier for the product, NOT the SKU.
fields.name: PRODUCT_ID

target.description: The numerical product number. Only used internally. All external communication should use the title or EAN.
target.name: ID

fields.description: The raw, pre-tax cost of the order. Note that this might be different in the future from the product price due to promotions, credits, etc.
fields.name: SUBTOTAL

fields.description: This is the amount of local and federal taxes that are collected on the purchase. Note that other governmental fees on some products are not included here, but instead are accounted for in the subtotal.
fields.name: TAX

fields.description: The total billed amount.
fields.name: TOTAL

fields.description: Discount amount.
fields.name: DISCOUNT

fields.description: The date and time an order was submitted.
fields.name: CREATED_AT

fields.description: Number of products bought.
fields.name: QUANTITY

kpis.description: The total sales revenue generated from all orders
kpis.business_value: This KPI provides an overview of the total income generated from sales, which is crucial for understanding the company's financial health.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT SUM(TOTAL) AS Total_Sales FROM ORDERS

kpis.description: The average value of each order
kpis.business_value: This KPI gives insight into the average income generated from each order, which can help in forecasting future revenues.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT AVG(TOTAL) AS Average_Order_Value FROM ORDERS
kpis.output_format: Single value representing average order value

kpis.description: The total quantity of products sold
kpis.business_value: This KPI provides information about the volume of products sold, which can be used to understand the demand for products.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT SUM(QUANTITY) AS Total_Quantity_Sold FROM ORDERS
kpis.output_format: Single value representing total quantity sold

kpis.description: The total value of discounts given on all orders
kpis.business_value: This KPI shows the total amount of discounts given, which can be used to analyze the impact of discounts on sales.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT SUM(DISCOUNT) AS Total_Discounts_Given FROM ORDERS
kpis.output_format: Single value representing total discounts given

kpis.description: The total amount of tax collected from all orders
kpis.business_value: This KPI provides information about the total tax collected, which is important for financial reporting and tax compliance.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT SUM(TAX) AS Total_Tax_Collected FROM ORDERS
kpis.output_format: Single value representing total tax collected

table_info.description: Includes a catalog of all the products ever sold by the famed Sample Company.

db.description: Some example data for you to play around with.
db.name: Sample Database
db.caveats: You probably don't want to use this for your business-critical analyses, but hey, it's your world, we're just living in it.
db.points_of_interest: You can find all sorts of different joinable tables ranging from products to people to reviews here.

table_info.name: PRODUCTS
table_info.caveats: The rating column is an integer from 1-5 where 1 is dreadful and 5 is the best thing ever.

fields.description: The numerical product number. Only used internally. All external communication should use the title or EAN.
fields.name: ID

fields.description: The international article number. A 13 digit number uniquely identifying the product.
fields.name: EAN

fields.description: The name of the product as it should be displayed to customers.
fields.name: TITLE

fields.description: The type of product, valid values include: Doohicky, Gadget, Gizmo and Widget
fields.name: CATEGORY

fields.description: The source of the product.
fields.name: VENDOR

fields.description: The list price of the product. Note that this is not always the price the product sold for due to discounts, promotions, etc.
fields.name: PRICE

fields.description: The average rating users have given the product. This ranges from 1 - 5
fields.name: RATING

fields.description: The date the product was added to our catalog.
fields.name: CREATED_AT

kpis.description: This KPI measures the average rating of all products in the catalog.
kpis.business_value: Understanding the average product rating can help the company identify overall customer satisfaction and product quality.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT AVG(RATING) FROM PRODUCTS

kpis.description: This KPI identifies the product category with the highest number of sales.
kpis.business_value: Knowing the most sold category can help the company focus its marketing and production efforts on popular categories.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT CATEGORY, COUNT(*) FROM PRODUCTS GROUP BY CATEGORY ORDER BY COUNT(*) DESC LIMIT 1

kpis.description: This KPI identifies the vendor whose products have the highest average rating.
kpis.business_value: Identifying the top rated vendor can help the company in making decisions about future collaborations and product sourcing.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT VENDOR, AVG(RATING) FROM PRODUCTS GROUP BY VENDOR ORDER BY AVG(RATING) DESC LIMIT 1

kpis.description: This KPI measures the average price of all products in the catalog.
kpis.business_value: Understanding the average product price can help the company in pricing strategy and market positioning.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT AVG(PRICE) FROM PRODUCTS

kpis.description: This KPI identifies the most recently added product to the catalog.
kpis.business_value: Knowing the newest product can help the company in promoting recent additions to their product line.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT TITLE FROM PRODUCTS ORDER BY CREATED_AT DESC LIMIT 1

kpis.description: This KPI measures the total number of likes each post has received.
kpis.business_value: This KPI can help identify the most popular posts and provide insights into user preferences.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT post_id, COUNT(user_id) as total_likes FROM tb_comm_post_like_users GROUP BY post_id

kpis.description: This KPI measures the total number of likes a user has given.
kpis.business_value: This KPI can help identify the most active users in terms of liking posts.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT user_id, COUNT(post_id) as total_likes FROM tb_comm_post_like_users GROUP BY user_id

kpis.description: This KPI measures the total number of likes given on each day.
kpis.business_value: This KPI can help identify trends in user activity and engagement over time.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT DATE(create_date) as date, COUNT(user_id) as total_likes FROM tb_comm_post_like_users GROUP BY date

kpis.description: This KPI measures the total number of likes each comment has received.
kpis.business_value: This KPI can help identify the most popular comments and provide insights into user preferences.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT comment_id, COUNT(user_id) as total_likes FROM tb_comm_post_like_users GROUP BY comment_id

kpis.description: This KPI measures the total number of unique users who have liked each post.
kpis.business_value: This KPI can help identify the reach of each post in terms of unique users.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT post_id, COUNT(DISTINCT user_id) as unique_users FROM tb_comm_post_like_users GROUP BY post_id

kpis.description: The total number of different products produced by each factory
kpis.business_value: This KPI helps to understand the diversity of products in each factory, which can be useful for resource allocation and strategic planning
kpis.sql_query: SELECT factory_id, COUNT(DISTINCT product) as total_products FROM tb_sales_products GROUP BY factory_id
kpis.output_format: A table with each row representing a factory and the total number of different products it produces

kpis.description: The top 5 products with the highest sales in each factory
kpis.business_value: This KPI helps to identify the most popular products in each factory, which can be used to drive marketing and sales strategies
kpis.sql_query: SELECT factory_id, product, RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY factory_id ORDER BY SUM(sales) DESC) as rank FROM tb_sales_products GROUP BY factory_id, product HAVING rank <= 5
kpis.output_format: A table with each row representing a factory and its top 5 products based on sales

kpis.description: The total sales of all products produced by each factory
kpis.business_value: This KPI helps to measure the productivity of each factory, which can be useful for performance evaluation and benchmarking
kpis.sql_query: SELECT factory_id, SUM(sales) as total_sales FROM tb_sales_products GROUP BY factory_id
kpis.output_format: A table with each row representing a factory and the total sales of all its products

kpis.description: The number of factories producing each product
kpis.business_value: This KPI helps to understand the popularity of each product across factories, which can be useful for market analysis and product development
kpis.sql_query: SELECT product, COUNT(DISTINCT factory_id) as total_factories FROM tb_sales_products GROUP BY product
kpis.output_format: A table with each row representing a product and the number of factories producing it

db.description: Internal Audit DB used to power metabase analytics.
db.name: Internal Metabase Database

kpis.description: The total number of users in the system.
kpis.business_value: This KPI provides a basic understanding of the size of the user base.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT COUNT(user_id) FROM v_users

kpis.description: The number of users who have joined within the last 30 days.
kpis.business_value: This KPI helps to understand the growth rate of the user base.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT COUNT(user_id) FROM v_users WHERE date_joined >= NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days'

kpis.description: The number of users who have logged in within the last 30 days.
kpis.business_value: This KPI helps to understand the engagement level of the user base.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT COUNT(user_id) FROM v_users WHERE last_login >= NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days'

kpis.description: The percentage of users who have not logged in for the last 90 days.
kpis.business_value: This KPI helps to understand the retention level of the user base.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT COUNT(user_id) FROM v_users WHERE last_login < NOW() - INTERVAL '90 days' / (SELECT COUNT(user_id) FROM v_users) * 100

kpis.description: The average number of days between each user's updates.
kpis.business_value: This KPI helps to understand the frequency of user interaction with the system.
kpis.sql_query: SELECT AVG(updated_at - LAG(updated_at, 1) OVER (PARTITION BY user_id ORDER BY updated_at)) FROM v_users
